<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910603-0100</DOCNO><DOCID>910603-0100.</DOCID><HL>   International:   Tokyo-Area Price Increase   Slowed to 3.0% in May   ----   Special to The Wall Street Journal</HL><DATE>06/03/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A7E</SO><IN>INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC AND MONETARY INDICATORS (IEI)INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC NEWS AND STATISTICS (IEN)</IN><NS>INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC NEWS AND ANALYSIS (IEN)</NS><RE>FAR EAST (FE)JAPAN (JA)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)</RE><LP>   TOKYO-- Annual growth in Tokyo-area consumer prices slowedto 3.0% in May from 3.3% in April, marking the fourthconsecutive month of decline since the index peaked at 4.3%in January.   The statistics bureau of the prime minister's office saidconsumer prices in the greater metropolitan area, an earlyindicator of price movements nationwide, rose 0.3% fromApril, slower than April's 0.4% rise from March.</LP><TEXT>   The Tokyo-area consumer price index stood at 111.8 in May,with 1985 equaling 100.   Yoshiro Tokunaga, price research division director of thegovernment's economic planning agency, said price pressurescontinue to calm, with factors that have pushed prices higheruntil now, such as fresh food and oil prices, declining inMay.   Mr. Tokunaga said that while caution is still required,there is ample reason to expect further improvements inprices over the medium term.</TEXT></DOC>